# Security in Java Programming

Java provides two levels of verification:

1. Compiler Level â€” â€” â€” Checks syntax (rules).

Reports syntax errors but does not care about execution meaning.

2. Execution Level (Runtime Environment) â€” â€” â€” Checks semantics (meaning).

If code is meaningless, throws Runtime Error.

ğŸ‘‰ Final Conclusion:
Compiler â†’ verifies Syntax

Runtime Environment (JVM) â†’ verifies Semantics

